      origin: primary
    - text: "Scope boundedness rated HIGH but test #2 alone defines a four-step end-to-end fixture (discovery → refine → lifecycle → critical-review) without bounding how the fixture is constructed, whether skill invocations are mocked or run live, what counts as 'produces', or how discovery_source field presence is validated. The 'exactly four test classes' framing hides substantial under-specified scope inside test #2."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Scope boundedness rated HIGH but test #1's assertion corpus is conditional on ticket #178's landing status; 'both can be done in parallel' hedge expands rather than bounds scope (now the implementer must handle either case)."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Requirements alignment rated HIGH but reasoning paraphrases requirements text rather than quoting from a verified read; 'Maintainability through simplicity' is in tension with adding four new test files plus a brittle line-number cross-reference scanner — alignment requires evidence the requirements affirmatively endorse this work, not just absence of conflict."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Requirements alignment HIGH partially rests on importing the project's 'high' criticality default for user-facing affordances from outside the ticket, conflating 'this work is in a load-bearing area' with 'requirements specify this work'."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Complexity rating 'complex' is asserted via surface metrics (file count, new test patterns) but does not engage with the cross-skill orchestration burden of test #2 (working fixture exercising four different skills end-to-end)."
      origin: primary
    - text: "Parent epic 172 frames itself around densification, deduplication of ~700 lines of cross-skill duplication, and vertical-planning adoption — child #181 instead adds four new test files (surface-area-additive, not subtractive) and does not target any of the four named bloat/duplication findings. The audit's 'Test/verification gaps (new class)' section plausibly sanctions this sub-thread, but the parent's 'vertical-planning adoption' half of the title creates an unaddressed expectation that the new test files might themselves adopt vertical-planning structure."
      origin: alignment
    - text: "Verification section's two deliberate-regression items are demonstration steps rather than acceptance criteria for the four test classes; 'clear, actionable error message' is qualitative with no rubric — the Verification list is shorter and softer than the HIGH rating implies."
      origin: primary
  dispositions:
    apply: 2
    dismiss: 5
    ask: 2
  applied_fixes:
    - "Revised Requirements alignment reasoning to cite the existing bin/cortex-check-parity CI-gate pattern (requirements/project.md Architectural Constraints) and clarify.md §3's 'high default for skill/lifecycle/hook/workflow changes' guidance, rather than leaning on the MEMORY user-facing-affordances framing. Rating remains HIGH; reasoning is now grounded in project-doc text and clarify-rubric guidance."
    - "Propagating the Parent Epic Alignment finding (origin: alignment) as a Research consideration: validate that #181 is a sanctioned sub-thread of the audit's 'Test/verification gaps (new class)' section, and explore whether the parent epic's vertical-planning-adoption theme implies the new test files should themselves adopt a vertical-planning structure rather than conventional pytest layout."
  dismissals:
